{"key":"processedPost-16264242","value":{"id":16264242,"first":16258699,"last":16267684,"when":1337647033,"utime":"05/22/12 03:37 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>Atlantic Wind said:</b><br />I trimmed the tall stumps up a bit. I did try twisting and pulling one and I ripped a chunk out of the substrate as I had predicted. I would definitely rather have a stump than a hole in the substrate. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />This is correct and there's lots of bad info in this thread.&nbsp; Mushrooms from some strains are barely attached to the substrate, and fruits often fall over when they get large.&nbsp; If you have one of these strains, go ahead and pull them off.<br /><br />However, other strains will be firmly attached to the substrate.&nbsp; If you twist and pull these you'll rip out a large chunk of substrate, and this wound is an open invitation for molds.<br /><br />Stems left over when cut close to the substrate do not rot(obviously because they're not vegetable-based garbage), nor do they invite mold since they're not uncolonized substrate.<br /><br /><blockquote>Quote:<br />I think the cutting will become outdated info at some point.<br /></blockquote><br /><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/wink.gif\" alt=\":wink:\" title=\":wink:\"/>&nbsp; We sterilize 480 lbs of substrate daily for our mushroom farm and cut every mushroom we grow to supply several supermarkets and every single restaurant in the county.&nbsp; We only pick by slicing fruits off at the base except for two strains of Agrocybe aegerita we grow which tend to fall over on their own.&nbsp; For these, we pull.&nbsp; For the cut ones, I've never once seen mold or bacteria start in the stump left over, and we're doing 3000 substrates monthly.<br />RR","title":"Re: Am I harvesting correctly?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}